'''Decree 1775''' was signed into [[Brazil]]ian law by President [[Fernando Henrique Cardoso]] on January 8, 1996.<ref name=":0">{{Cite journal|last=Moore|first=Sara Gavney|last2=Lemos|first2=Maria Carmen|date=1999-05-01|title=Indigenous Policy in Brazil: The Development of Decree 1775 and the Proposed Raposa/Serra do Sol Reserve, Roraima, Brazil|url=https://muse.jhu.edu/article/13670|journal=Human Rights Quarterly|volume=21|issue=2|pages=444–463|doi=10.1353/hrq.1999.0026|issn=1085-794X}}</ref> The decree changed the steps [[Fundação Nacional do Índio|FUNAI]] was required to follow to demarcate indigenous lands, effectively making the process more complicated and allowing for more interference from commercial interests.<ref name=":1">{{Cite journal|last=Rodrigues|first=Maria Guadalupe|year=|title=Indigenous Rights in Democratic Brazil|url=http://www.umass.edu/legal/Benavides/Fall2005/397U/Readings%20Legal%20397U/13%20Moog%20Rodrigues.pdf|journal=Human Rights Quarterly|volume=|pages=|doi=10.1353/hrq.2002.0028}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Perz|first=Stephen|year=|title=CONTRIBUTIONS OF RACIAL-ETHNIC RECLASSIFICATION AND DEMOGRAPHIC PROCESSES TO INDIGENOUS POPULATION RESURGENCE|url=https://www.researchgate.net/profile/David_Kennedy5/publication/236827219_Contributions_of_Racial-Ethnic_Reclassification_and_Demographic_Processes_to_Indigenous_Population_Resurgence_The_Case_of_Brazil/links/540602800cf2bba34c1e3af5.pdf|journal=Latin American Research Review|volume=43|pages=|via=}}</ref> Individuals or companies were allowed from the beginning of the demarcation process until 90 days after FUNAI issued their report to submit an appeal showing that the contested lands do not meet the qualifications of indigenous lands as stated in the constitution.<ref name=":0" /> The decree also placed the final decision in the hands of the [[Justice ministry|Minister of Justice]], which left the fate of indigenous lands vulnerable to various political ideologies.<ref name=":1" /> The government claimed that allowing people to contest indigenous lands during the demarcation process would prevent any future challenges of completed lands on the basis of unconstitutionality.<ref name=":0" /> The decree was widely contested as a violation of indigenous rights, earning the nickname of the "Genocide Decree," due to the power it gave to commercial interests to exploit Indian lands.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Anderson|first=Samara|year=2003|title=Colonialism Continues: A Comparative Analysis of the United States and Brazil's Exploitation of Indigenous Peoples' Forest Resources|url=http://heinonline.org/HOL/Page?handle=hein.journals/umialr53&div=35&g_sent=1&collection=journals|journal=Vermont Law Review|volume=|pages=|via=}}</ref> By April 1996, FUNAI had received over 500 appeals for over 40 indigenous territories that were in the process of being demarcated.<ref name=":0" /><ref name=":5">{{Cite web|url=http://www.cidh.org/countryrep/brazil-eng/chaper%206%20.htm|title=Brazil 1997 - Chapter VI|website=www.cidh.org|access-date=2016-11-16}}</ref> FUNAI followed procedure and submitted its official opinion to the Ministry of Justice, rejecting the appeals that were brought against the indigenous lands.<ref name=":0" /><ref name=":5" /> Justice [[Nelson Jobim]] sided with FUNAI on all except eight territories, ordering further investigation.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Simmons|first=Cynthia S.|title=The Local Articulation of Policy Conflict: Land Use, Environment, and Amerindian Rights in Eastern Amazonia|url=http://www.tandfonline.com/doi/pdf/10.1111/0033-0124.00343|journal=The Professional Geographer|volume=54|issue=3|pages=241–258|doi=10.1111/0033-0124.00343}}</ref>
