{{Infobox court case |name = Eight Mile Style vs New Zealand National Party |court = [[High Court of New Zealand]] at Wellington |image = Coat of arms of New Zealand.svg |full name = |date decided = {{start date|2017|10|25|df=y}} |citations = [2017] NZHC 2603 |ECLI = |transcripts = [http://www.courtsofnz.govt.nz/static-files/Eight-Mile-Style-v-National-Party-final-25-October-2017.pdf Judgment] |judges = Helen Cull |number of judges = 1 |decision by = |concurring = |dissenting = |concur/dissent = |prior actions = |appealed from = |appealed to = |subsequent actions = |related actions = |opinions = |keywords = {{hlist |[[Copyright Act 1994]]}} |italic title = }}
A controversy was caused in [[New Zealand]] in 2014 when the [[New Zealand National Party|National Party]] allegedly used the song "[[Lose Yourself]]" by the American rapper [[Eminem]] in a campaign advertisement during [[New Zealand general election, 2014|that year's election]]. The Wellington High Court ruled against the National Party, ordering them to pay over $600,000 for copyright infringement.
==Background== On 16 September 2016, [[Eminem]]'s publishers filed a lawsuit with the [[High Court of New Zealand|High Court]] in Wellington, claiming that the National Party had made a copyright infringement from using an instrumental version of the song "[[Lose Yourself]]" in television advertisements without their consent. Their campaign manager [[Steven Joyce]] stated their using of the song was "pretty legal", claiming it had been purchased from an Australian music library.<ref>{{cite news |title= Eminem suing New Zealand's National party for allegedly using his song |url= https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/sep/16/eminem-suing-new-zealands-national-party-for-allegedly-using-his-song |publisher= The Guardian |date= 16 September 2014 |accessdate= 17 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |first= Nikki |last= Papatsoumas |date= 16 September 2014 |title= National Party sued over Eminem copyright infringment |url= http://www.nzherald.co.nz/entertainment/news/article.cfm?c_id=1501119&objectid=11325727 |publisher= The New Zealand Herald |accessdate= 17 September 2014}}</ref> The publishers counter-claimed that they never allowed the song to be used in a political advert. They have persisted with the lawsuit and a trial began at the [[Wellington]] High Court on 1 May 2017.<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |date= 8 September 2016 |title= Court date set for Eminem vs New Zealand National Party |url= https://nz.news.yahoo.com/top-stories/a/32565722/court-date-set-for-eminem-vs-new-zealand-national-party-copyright-infringement-case/#page1 |publisher= Yahoo News |accessdate= 8 September 2016}}</ref> The case concluded on 12 May 2017; Justice Helen Cull reserved her decision.<ref>[http://www.nzherald.co.nz/entertainment/news/article.cfm?c_id=1501119&objectid=11855413 It's a rap: Eminem lawsuit against New Zealand party ends] New Zealand Herald, 12 May 2017</ref> On 25 October, the High Court ruled that the National Party had breached copyright and ordered them to pay $600,000 plus interest.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/entertainment/music/95132686/national-party-loses-court-decision-on-use-of-eminemesque-song|title=National Party loses copyright case over use of Eminem-esque, ordered to pay $600k|date=2017-10-25|publisher=Stuff.co.nz}}</ref>
==Aftermath== [[Eight Mile Style]] spokesman Joel Martin said the company was happy with the result following a "distasteful" trial for them, while National Party president Peter Goodfellow said the party was disappointed with the final verdict and would proceed themselves to pursue legal action against Labrador and Beatbox, who supplied them the music.<ref name="insulting">{{cite news|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/politics/news/article.cfm?c_id=280&objectid=11936806 |title=National Party 'insulting' in action over Eminem copyright |date=26 October 2017 |publisher=[[The New Zealand Herald]] |accessdate=27 October 2017}}</ref> Eminem told ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' that he was not consulted about the case, but should he receive any money from it he would donate it to charity for the [[Hurricane Harvey]] relief efforts.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.radionz.co.nz/news/political/342482/eminem-to-donate-legal-win-money-to-charity |title=Eminem to donate legal win money to charity |date=27 October 2017 |publisher=Radio New Zealand |accessdate=27 October 2017}}</ref> Musician and former [[Australasian Performing Right Association|APRA]] director [[Mike Chunn]] said that [[sound-alike]] recordings are routinely used in advertising and that the ruling was unfair.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.radionz.co.nz/news/national/342383/music-rights-specialist-backs-national-over-eminem-esque |title=Music rights specialist backs National over 'Eminem Esque' |date=27 October 2017 |publisher=Radio New Zealand |accessdate=26 October 2017}}</ref>
The National Party are set to appeal the ruling saying the damages should have been lower and a cross-appeal from US companies Eight Mile Style and Martin Affiliated seek the damages to be increased.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/entertainment/100082877/appeal-grounds-revealed-in-eminem-copyright-case-against-national-party |title=Appeal grounds revealed in Eminem copyright case against National Party |date=21 December 2017 |publisher=[[Stuff.co.nz]] |accessdate=23 December 2017}}</ref>
