'''Good neighborliness''' is a [[Sources_of_international_law#General_principles_of_law|general principle]] of [[international law]] with particular importance for the field of [[international environmental law]].  The principle "obligates states to try to reconcile their interests with the interests of neighboring states",<ref>{{cite journal|title = New Perspectives on International Environmental Law | journal = The Yale Law Journal | volume = 82 | issue = 8 |date=July 1973 | page = 1664 | doi=10.2307/795366}}</ref>  and found expression in a number of 20th Century international legal rulings, most notably the [[Trail,_British_Columbia#Trail_smelter_arbitration|Trail smelter arbitration]] between the United States and Canada.<ref>{{cite book|title = Globalization Redux: New Name, Same Game |pages = 85–86 | publisher = University Press of America | isbn = 0-7618-2922-9 }}</ref>

